<p>Using groebner basis for constraint satisfaction problems: x^n=1 gives a root of unity. There are n solutions. This gives a finite set to work with. Then you can add more equations. This is related to the max-cut thing. I saw this on Cox webpage.</p>

<p>You can require neighbors to have different vertices by  0=(xi^k - xj^k)/(xi - xj). You can encode many constraints using clever algebra.</p>

